The Microsoft AI-102 certification validates your expertise and opens doors to higher-paying roles in IT and cybersecurity. Whether you are just starting your study journey or doing a final review, this guide breaks down everything you need to know to pass the AI-102 exam.

## Exam Overview

- **Certification:** Microsoft AI-102
- **Exam Code:** AI-102
- **Vendor:** Microsoft
- **Cost:** $165 USD
- **Duration:** 150 minutes
- **Questions:** 40-60 questions
- **Passing Score:** 700 out of 1000
- **Format:** Multiple choice, case studies, drag-and-drop
- **Prerequisites:** AI-900 recommended but not required

## Domain Breakdown

Understanding the exam domains and their weights is critical for efficient study planning. Focus more time on heavily-weighted domains while ensuring you cover all areas.

### Domain 1: Plan and Manage an Azure AI Solution (15-20%)

- 1.1 Select the appropriate Azure AI service
- 1.2 Plan, create, and deploy an Azure AI service
- 1.3 Manage Azure AI services
- 1.4 Implement responsible AI practices

**Key concepts:** Azure AI Services, Resource Provisioning, Multi-Service Resources, Authentication Keys and Endpoints, Managed Identities, Virtual Network Integration, Diagnostic Logging, Responsible AI Principles

### Domain 2: Implement Content Moderation Solutions (10-15%)

- 2.1 Analyze text content for moderation
- 2.2 Analyze image content for moderation
- 2.3 Implement Azure AI Content Safety

**Key concepts:** Azure AI Content Safety, Text Moderation, Image Moderation, Severity Levels, Custom Categories, Blocklists, Content Safety Studio, Moderation Workflows

### Domain 3: Implement Computer Vision Solutions (15-20%)

- 3.1 Analyze images using Azure AI Vision
- 3.2 Implement custom image classification and object detection
- 3.3 Analyze video content
- 3.4 Implement facial recognition solutions

**Key concepts:** Azure AI Vision, Image Analysis API, Custom Vision, Object Detection, Image Classification, Face API, OCR and Read API, Spatial Analysis

### Domain 4: Implement Natural Language Processing Solutions (30-35%)

- 4.1 Analyze text by using Azure AI Language
- 4.2 Build conversational language understanding models
- 4.3 Create a question answering solution
- 4.4 Implement Azure OpenAI solutions
- 4.5 Implement text translation

**Key concepts:** Text Analytics, Sentiment Analysis, Named Entity Recognition, Conversational Language Understanding, Custom Question Answering, Azure OpenAI Service, Prompt Engineering, Chat Completions API

### Domain 5: Implement Knowledge Mining and Document Intelligence (15-20%)

- 5.1 Implement Azure AI Search
- 5.2 Create an enrichment pipeline with built-in skills
- 5.3 Implement custom skills and knowledge stores
- 5.4 Implement Azure AI Document Intelligence

**Key concepts:** Azure AI Search, Search Indexers, Skillsets, Built-In Skills, Custom Skills, Knowledge Store, Semantic Ranking, Azure AI Document Intelligence


## Recommended Study Timeline

Plan for approximately **10-16 weeks** of dedicated study. Here is a suggested weekly breakdown:

- **Week 1:** Planning: Azure AI services overview, resource provisioning, security
- **Week 2:** Planning: Responsible AI, monitoring, logging, cost management
- **Week 3:** Content Moderation: Azure AI Content Safety, text/image moderation
- **Week 4:** Computer Vision: Image Analysis, Custom Vision, object detection
- **Week 5:** Computer Vision: Face API, OCR, spatial analysis, Video Indexer
- **Week 6:** NLP: Text Analytics, sentiment analysis, key phrase extraction
- **Week 7:** NLP: Language Understanding (CLU), question answering, translation
- **Week 8:** NLP: Azure OpenAI Service, prompt engineering, chat completions
- **Week 9:** Knowledge Mining: Azure AI Search, indexers, skillsets, custom skills
- **Week 10:** Document Intelligence: Form Recognizer, custom models, prebuilt models
- **Week 11:** Integration: Bot Framework, orchestration workflows, solution deployment
- **Week 12:** Full Review: Practice exams, hands-on AI labs, weak area focus

## Top Study Tips

1. **Start with the official exam objectives.** Download them from the Microsoft website and use them as your study checklist. Every exam question maps to a specific objective.

2. **Use active recall over passive reading.** Instead of re-reading notes, test yourself with practice questions after each study session. This dramatically improves retention.

3. **Focus on heavily-weighted domains first.** Domains with higher percentages appear more on the exam. Master these before moving to lower-weighted areas.

4. **Build hands-on experience.** Set up a lab environment and practice the skills you are studying. Hands-on experience is especially valuable for performance-based questions.

5. **Take practice exams under real conditions.** Time yourself, eliminate distractions, and simulate the exam environment. Review every wrong answer and understand why it was wrong.

